-- Japan, Philippines, South Korea, Indonesia: Asia Bonds, Currency Preview
-- B y   F r a n c e s   Y o o n
-- 2010-11-08T23:11:04Z
-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2010-11-08/japan-philippines-south-korea-indonesia-asia-bonds-currency-preview.html
The following events and economic
reports may influence trading in Asia’s local bonds and
currencies today. Bond yields and exchange rates are from the
previous trading session unless stated otherwise.  Japan: Chief Cabinet Secretary Yoshito Sengoku and Finance
Minister Yoshihiko Noda will hold media briefings after a
Cabinet meeting in the morning. Sengoku will have another press
briefing at 4 p.m. in Tokyo.  The Ministry of Finance will release at 8:50 a.m. in Tokyo
its report on the nation’s current account balance for September.
Japan’s current account surplus widened to 1.7 trillion yen
($20.9 billion) in September from 1.1 trillion yen in August,
according to a Bloomberg News survey of economists.  The Cabinet Office will release at 2 p.m. in Tokyo its
report on the Economy Watchers index, a survey of barbers, taxi
drivers and others who deal with consumers, for October.  The yield on the 1 percent government bond due September
2020 was at 0.96 percent, according to Japan Bond Trading Co.,
the nation’s largest interdealer debt broker. A basis point is
0.01 percentage point.  The yen traded at 81.15 per dollar at 8:06 a.m. in Tokyo.  South Korea: The Bank of Korea will announce producer
prices for October. Prices rose 4 percent from a year earlier in
September, the fastest pace in three months.  The yield on the 3.75 percent debt due June 2013 was 3.55
percent. The won was at 1,113.23 per dollar.  Thailand: The Bank of Thailand will sell 65 billion baht
($2.2 billion) of 28-, 91- and 182-day bills.  The yield on the 5.85 percent note due March 2021 was 3.25
percent. The baht was at 29.64 per dollar.  Indonesia: Bank Indonesia is expected to sell five- and 10-
year government bonds and one-year treasury bills.  The yield on the 11 percent bond due November 2020 was at
7.33 percent, according to midday prices from the Inter Dealer
Market Association. The rupiah was at 8,909 per dollar.  Philippines: The Bureau of the Treasury will auction 8
billion pesos ($185 million) of 10-year bonds at 1 p.m. local
time today.  Treasurer Roberto Tan may comment on the planned peso bond
swap after the auction. Finance Secretary Cesar Purisima may
comment on the budget deficit and economic targets during a
Senate hearing today.  The yield on the 6.125 percent debt due September 2020 was
5.97 percent, according to Philippine Dealing & Exchange Corp.
The peso was at 43.22 per dollar.  To contact the editor responsible for this story:
